## 3. Shared Infrastructure — `p6lab.ingestion`

### 3.1 Triple-view emitter (`triple_view.py`)

Implements Phase 4 of the staircase plan ([staircase:L250-280](./staircase-engine-plan-of-action.md#L250-L280))
and the dual-view methodology from [OB-reference.md:769-788](./OB-reference.md#L769-L788).

**Responsibility:** given a raw replay, emit time-aligned triples:

```python
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class TripleFrame:
    timestamp_ms: int
    symbol: str
    # L3 truth — full order lifecycle slice for this window
    l3_events: list[Order]
    l3_book_snapshot: OrderBookSnapshot
    # L2 shadow — aggregated per-level depth
    l2_features: np.ndarray           # 12-dim (§4.2)
    l2_book_vector: np.ndarray        # 40-dim book_shape_vector
    # L1 footprint — top-of-book derived state
    l1_features: np.ndarray           # 16-dim (§4.1)
```

**Window granularities:** 100ms fast / 1s standard / 5s slow, emitted in
parallel to separate parquet files. Downstream consumers pick.

**Important:** this module does *not* render anything. It only prepares
data. All visualization goes through the frontend (§10). Notebooks 03-07
read the parquet files it writes; the web server also reads them for
replay-mode triple view.

### 3.2 Event windowing (`event_windowing.py`)

`WindowIterator` with pluggable anchoring strategies — burst-anchored for
pattern mining (04), fixed-horizon for labeling (§5.3), fixed-length for
correlation grids (06).

### 3.3 Instrument normalizer (`instrument_normalizer.py`)

Implements [OB-reference.md:453-468](./OB-reference.md#L453-L468): depth
as ratio of 20-day median, spread in basis points, ATR-normalized price
moves, self-normalizing book shape vector, VIX-tagged regime buckets
(low <15, normal 15-25, elevated 25-35, high >35).

Per-instrument backfill tables cached in
`artifacts/p6lab/normalization/{symbol}_median_depth.parquet`.

---

## 4. Shared Infrastructure — `p6lab.features`

### 4.1 L1 feature set (`l1_features.py`)

16 features per [OB-reference.md:830-847](./OB-reference.md#L830-L847):

| # | Feature | Update | Formula |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `spread_ticks` | every L1 | `(best_ask - best_bid) / tick_size` |
| 2 | `spread_bps_l1` | every L1 | `spread_ticks × tick_size / mid × 10000` |
| 3 | `best_bid_size` | every L1 | raw |
| 4 | `best_ask_size` | every L1 | raw |
| 5 | `top_imbalance` | every L1 | `(bid_sz - ask_sz) / (bid_sz + ask_sz)` |
| 6 | `bid_refresh_rate` | 100ms roll | passive adds at best bid per second |
| 7 | `ask_refresh_rate` | 100ms roll | passive adds at best ask per second |
| 8 | `bid_retreat_velocity` | 250ms roll | negative Δ best_bid per second |
| 9 | `ask_advance_velocity` | 250ms roll | positive Δ best_ask per second |
| 10 | `spread_compression_rate` | 250ms roll | Δ spread per second (negative = tightening) |
| 11 | `tick_direction_streak` | every L1 | consecutive same-sign Δ mid |
| 12 | `tick_acceleration` | 500ms roll | `d²(tick_count)/dt²` |
| 13 | `trade_at_bid_ratio` | 1s roll | `trades_at_bid / total_trades` |
| 14 | `size_spike_ratio` | 1s roll | `max_trade_size / median_trade_size` |
| 15 | `microprice_velocity` | 250ms roll | Δ microprice per second |
| 16 | `l1_shape_vector` | every L1 | `[bid_sz, ask_sz, spread_bps, imbalance]` normalized |

Exports `compute_l1_features(snapshot, history) → np.ndarray[16]` for
per-snapshot use (called from web server at replay time) and
`compute_l1_series(snapshots) → pd.DataFrame` for bulk backtesting
(called from notebooks).

### 4.2 L2 feature set (`l2_features.py`)

12 features per [OB-reference.md:432-451](./OB-reference.md#L432-L451): bid_ask_imbalance,
depth_ratio, weighted_mid, spread_bps, depth_within_pct, imbalance_ema,
depth_change_rate_5s, depth_change_rate_30s, level_persistence,
refresh_rate, book_shape_vector (40-dim), trade_flow_toxicity (VPIN).

### 4.3 Fragility Index (`fragility_index.py`)

Direct port of [OB-reference.md:1552-1696](./OB-reference.md#L1552-L1696).
Six sub-indices (DF, CF, RF, SF, FT, CIS) and two composites:

```python
FI_fast = 0.35 × RF + 0.35 × SF + 0.30 × FT                # L1 speed, <5ms
FI_full = 0.20 × DF + 0.15 × CF + 0.20 × RF + \
          0.15 × SF + 0.15 × FT + 0.15 × CIS               # L2 speed, <50ms
```

Used by notebook 07 (cascade validation) and surfaced live by
[fragility_gauge.js](#105-fragility-gauge-panel) (§10.5).

Validation criteria from [OB-reference.md:1734-1748](./OB-reference.md#L1734-L1748):
AUC > 0.70 for predicting >2 ATR moves within 30m, FI > 0.5 at least 2m
before 50% of cascades, FP rate <30% at FI > 0.7.

### 4.4 VPIN (`vpin.py`)

Volume-synchronized PIN from [OB-reference.md:1625-1644](./OB-reference.md#L1625-L1644).
Lee-Ready or BVC classification. Feeds `l2_features.trade_flow_toxicity`
and `fragility_index.FT`.

---

## 5. Pattern Library (`p6lab.patterns`)

### 5.1 Library schema (`library.py`)

Versioned YAML registry at `artifacts/p6lab/pattern_library/library.yaml`:

```yaml
version: 1
generated: 2026-04-10
patterns:
  iceberg_accumulation:
    l3_signature: |
      refill_count ≥ 4, max_visible_size ≤ 8, total_volume ≥ 30
    l2_manifestation: |
      stable level, no depletion despite prints, refresh_rate > 8/sec
    l1_footprint: |
      tight spread, elevated BBO refresh rate, stable best_bid_size
    outcome_distribution:
      horizon_1m:  {mean_atr: 0.42, std: 0.81, hit_rate: 0.61, n: 2341}
      horizon_5m:  {mean_atr: 0.89, std: 1.20, hit_rate: 0.67, n: 2341}
    min_sample_size: 200
    regime_specific: true
    instruments: [NQ, ES]
    confidence_tier_cutoffs: {A: 0.85, B: 0.72, C: 0.60}
    status: active   # or candidate, retired
    validation_hash: sha256:...
```

Pydantic `PatternDefinition` model for validation. Read by notebooks 04
and 06, by the pattern review queue UI (§10.3), and at runtime by the
live correlation engine (§10.4, §11.4).

**Minimum sample size rule:** 200 occurrences minimum per
[OB-reference.md:805-809](./OB-reference.md#L805-L809). Below threshold →
`status: candidate`, no outcome distribution until promoted.

### 5.2 Unsupervised miner (`miner.py`)

HDBSCAN-based pattern discovery beyond the seven hand-coded ones:

1. Burst-anchor windowing via `event_windowing.WindowIterator`
2. 30-dim event shape vector per window (add/cancel ratio, burst
   intensity, spread dynamics, level crossings, size percentiles,
   inter-event intervals, side asymmetry, lifecycle entropy)
3. Instrument normalization (§3.3)
4. HDBSCAN with `min_cluster_size=50`, `min_samples=25`
5. Forward-outcome labeling at 1m/5m/15m/1h
6. Filter: n≥200, hit_rate_5m > 0.55, Sharpe > 0.3, cosine distance to
   existing patterns > 0.3
7. Write to `artifacts/p6lab/pattern_library/mined_candidates/` as
   parquet (one row per candidate cluster) + one exemplar window set
   per cluster

The **promotion decision** happens in the web UI, not in the notebook:
notebook 04 writes candidates to disk, the `pattern_review_queue.js`
frontend panel (§10.3) loads them one at a time in the triple view and
lets a human accept / reject / defer with one click. Accept writes to
`library.yaml` with `status: mined_approved`.

### 5.3 Labeler (`labeler.py`)

`PatternOutcome` dataclass with raw + ATR-normalized moves at 1m/5m/15m/1h
and continuation/reversal/neutral classification vs per-instrument ATR
threshold (0.5 ATR per [OB-reference.md:805-809](./OB-reference.md#L805-L809)).

### 5.4 Template matcher (`template_matcher.py`)

Cosine similarity on `l2_features.book_shape_vector` time series, per
[OB-reference.md:470-487](./OB-reference.md#L470-L487):

```
ensemble_score = 0.40 × template_match
               + 0.35 × feature_distance_mahalanobis
               + 0.25 × contextual_score          # TOD, VIX, volume
```

Mahalanobis covariance via Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage; fallback to Euclidean
if condition number κ(Σ) > 1000. Consumed by notebook 06 (as ML baseline)
and by the live correlation engine at runtime (§7.1, §10.4).

---

## 6. Execution (`p6lab.execution`)

**Critical:** this module is shared between the batch notebook (05) and
the interactive UI tool (§10.2). Same library, two consumers.

### 6.1 Queue tracker (`queue_tracker.py`)

Per-order absolute queue position tracker ingesting MBO events:

```python
class QueueTracker:
    def place_limit_order(
        self, timestamp_ms: int, side: Side, price: float, size: float
    ) -> OrderHandle: ...

    def on_event(self, event: Order) -> None:
        """Update all tracked orders: advance on fills ahead of us,
        demote on cancels ahead of us, etc."""

    def get_position(self, handle: OrderHandle) -> QueuePosition:
        """Absolute position from front of queue, in contracts."""
```

This is the missing infrastructure flagged in
[staircase:L74-80](./staircase-engine-plan-of-action.md#L74-L80).

### 6.2 Fill simulator (`fill_simulator.py`)

Given a simulated limit order at time t, walk the event stream forward
and produce:

```python
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class FillOutcome:
    filled: bool
    filled_size: float
    fill_timestamp_ms: int | None
    queue_position_at_entry: float
    queue_position_at_fill: float | None
    adverse_ticks_at_fill: int
    realized_pnl: float
    fill_reason: Literal["full", "partial", "adverse_exit", "timeout", "cancelled"]
    # New: per-step trajectory for UI rendering
    trajectory: list[QueueSnapshot]   # empty if run in bulk mode
```

**Two modes:**
- `simulate_bulk(orders)` — vectorized, no trajectory, called by notebook 05
  to run 10,000+ trades for statistical P(fill) distributions
- `simulate_interactive(order)` — returns full trajectory list for
  per-step animation, called by the UI virtual-order tool (§10.2)

### 6.3 Cost model (`cost_model.py`)

Realistic cost decomposition: crossed-spread cost, commission,
adverse-selection cost from `FillOutcome.adverse_ticks_at_fill`,
opportunity cost on unfilled orders. Replaces the naive
`slippage + commission` model in `WRAP_P6_BACKTEST.ipynb` §07.

---

## 7. Correlation Engine (`p6lab.correlation`)

### 7.1 Engine (`engine.py`)

Runtime module: live L2 (+ optional L1) state → matched patterns with
scores. Pure-Python implementation of
[OB-reference.md:356-549](./OB-reference.md#L356-L549).

```python
class CorrelationEngine:
    def __init__(
        self,
        library: PatternLibrary,
        matcher: TemplateMatcher,
        scorer: EnsembleScorer,
        regime_classifier: Callable,
    ): ...

    def match(
        self,
        l2_window: pd.DataFrame,      # last 30s-5m of L2 features
        l1_window: pd.DataFrame | None,
        context: MatchContext,        # TOD, VIX regime, instrument
    ) -> list[PatternMatch]:
        """All patterns matching above threshold, sorted by score."""
```

Latency target: <50ms per match ([OB-reference.md:476](./OB-reference.md#L476)).
Unit-tested against synthetic inputs before any consumer wires it up.

**Consumers:** notebook 06 (training + validation), `correlation_api.py`
(server wiring, §11.4), `correlation_feed.js` (UI, §10.4).

### 7.2 Scorer (`scorer.py`)

Confidence tier assignment per [OB-reference.md:500-507](./OB-reference.md#L500-L507):
>0.85 = A (auto-alert + sizing), 0.72-0.85 = B (alert only), 0.60-0.72 =
C (log only), <0.60 = discard.

### 7.3 Regime conditioner (`regime_conditioner.py`)

Per-instrument, per-VIX-bucket template selection
([OB-reference.md:464-466](./OB-reference.md#L464-L466)).

---

## 8. Validation (`p6lab.validation`)

### 8.1 CPCV (`cpcv.py`)

Combinatorial Purged Cross-Validation with 14-day cascade-event embargo
per [OB-reference.md:1804-1905](./OB-reference.md#L1804-L1905). Wraps
`specs/cv/cv_combinatorial.py` with the extra cascade-timestamp
constraint. Required for notebook 07 and available to 03/04/06.

### 8.2 Synthetic augmentation (`augmentation.py`)

Port of [OB-reference.md:1336-1537](./OB-reference.md#L1336-L1537): time
stretch/compress, depth scaling ±20%, volatility shift ±1 ATR,
cross-instrument transfer, phase duration jitter. Each augmented
sample tagged with `augmentation_method`; notebook 07 enforces "must
beat original-only baseline" per
[OB-reference.md:1504-1509](./OB-reference.md#L1504-L1509).

### 8.3 Information-gain gate (`information_gain.py`)

Enforces [staircase:L523](./staircase-engine-plan-of-action.md#L523):
"No component gets added unless it beats baseline by measurable margin."

```python
def must_beat_baseline(
    candidate_metric: float,
    baseline_metric: float,
    min_improvement: float = 0.02,
    n_bootstrap: int = 1000,
) -> DecisionReport: ...
```

Used by notebooks 03/04/06 when promoting features or patterns.

---

## 9. Notebook Specifications (batch workloads)

### 9.1 Notebook 03 — `WRAP_P6_L1_FEATURE_LAB.ipynb`

**Purpose:** build and validate the 16-feature L1 set + 12-feature L2
set. Answers: *which book-state features have forward-return edge?*

**Sections:** 00 env → 01 triple-view replay (writes `triple_view/*.parquet`
for all downstream notebooks and the web server) → 02 L1 features → 03
L2 features → 04 univariate analysis (Spearman, ROC-AUC, Brier) → 05
mutual information vs forward direction → 06 RF + SHAP importance with
PurgedKFold → 07 redundancy pruning → 08 information-gain gate (each
feature must beat `bid_ask_imbalance` baseline by ≥2% AUC) → 09
Fragility Index validation → 10 report.

**Produces:** canonical `triple_view/{symbol}.parquet` consumed by every
other notebook and by the web server for live L1/L2 feature rendering.

### 9.2 Notebook 04 — `WRAP_P6_PATTERN_MINING.ipynb`

**Purpose:** unsupervised L3 pattern discovery beyond the seven
hand-coded patterns.

**Sections:** 00 env → 01 load triple-view → 02 burst windowing → 03
30-dim event shape extraction → 04 UMAP projection (visual only) → 05
HDBSCAN clustering → 06 cluster profiling → 07 forward-outcome labeling
→ 08 distance-to-existing check → 09 candidate filter → 10 **write
candidates to `mined_candidates/*.parquet` with exemplar windows** for
human review in the UI (§10.3).

**Hand-off:** this notebook does *not* decide whether candidates get
promoted. It writes them to disk; the web UI pattern review queue
(§10.3) is where a human accepts or rejects each one. Only accepted
patterns reach `library.yaml` with `status: mined_approved`.

### 9.3 Notebook 05 — `WRAP_P6_EXECUTION_SIM.ipynb` (batch only)

**Purpose:** statistical fill-probability and queue-priority analysis
over large trade populations.

**Sections:** 00 env → 01 replay with queue tracker → 02 signal source
(aggregator frame log + correlation engine output) → 03 bulk passive
simulation via `fill_simulator.simulate_bulk` → 04 queue-position
conditional P(fill) by quintile → 05 aggressive vs passive entry
comparison → 06 step-ahead economics → 07 signal-to-tradeable
conversion rate per strategy class → 08 realistic PnL backtest → 09
report.

**Explicitly NOT in this notebook:** single-order "place here and see what
happens" exploration. That lives in [§10.2](#102-virtual-order-tool) as
an interactive UI tool. Both consume `p6lab.execution.fill_simulator`;
the split is between `simulate_bulk` (notebook) and
`simulate_interactive` (UI).

### 9.4 Notebook 06 — `WRAP_P6_CORRELATION_LAB.ipynb`

**Purpose:** train and validate the correlation engine. Answers: *how
well can L1+L2 features predict the L3 pattern label the omniscient
teacher saw?*

**Sections:** 00 env → 01 load triple-view + library → 02 L3 label
assignment (multi-label OK) → 03 dataset construction
`X = concat(L1, L2, fragility)` → 04 PurgedKFold RF + LightGBM → 05
per-pattern precision-recall (target >65% per
[OB-reference.md:485](./OB-reference.md#L485)) → 06 template-matcher
baseline (ML must beat it by ≥2%) → 07 two-stage architecture
(L1-only Stage 1 + L1+L2 Stage 2) → 08 correlation heatmap (L1↔L3
mutual information) → 09 regime conditioning → 10 engine dry run
with <50ms latency check → 11 information-gain gate → 12 report +
**model export** to `correlation_runs/models/{version}.pkl` for the
web server to load (§11.4).

### 9.5 Notebook 07 — `WRAP_P6_CASCADE_LAB.ipynb`

**Purpose:** cascade detection and forecasting. Answers: *when should we
abstain or flip to risk-off?*

**Sections:** 00 env → 01 historical cascade event identification → 02
pre-cascade window extraction → 03 CPCV with 14-day embargo → 04 FI
predictive power (AUC target >0.70) → 05 lead-time distribution
(≥2min before 50% of cascades) → 06 FP rate at FI > 0.7 (<30% target)
→ 07 synthetic augmentation comparison vs baseline → 08 per-cascade-type
classifier (Type A/B/C/D) → 09 cross-instrument stress (CIS) → 10 report
+ **FI model export** for the web server fragility gauge (§10.5, §11.4).

