## 10. Frontend Specifications (interactive workloads)

All five UI components extend the existing `projects/p6-v2/web/` frontend.
They reuse the existing WebSocket client
([websocket_client.js](../../projects/p6-v2/web/js/websocket_client.js)),
chart ([chart.js](../../projects/p6-v2/web/js/chart.js)), replay
controls ([replay_controls.js](../../projects/p6-v2/web/js/replay_controls.js)),
and depth overlay
([depth_overlay.js](../../projects/p6-v2/web/js/depth_overlay.js)).

### 10.1 Triple View Panel

**File:** `web/js/triple_view_panel.js` (new)
**Activated by:** toggle button in existing
[control_panel.js](../../projects/p6-v2/web/js/control_panel.js)

**Layout:** three stacked panels with a shared x-axis and shared
scrubber. When active, the main chart shrinks to the top 40%, the new
panels occupy the remaining 60%:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Main chart (40% height) — existing lightweight-charts candles│
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ L3 event lane (20% height) — NEW                             │
│   Per-order timeline: add / modify / cancel / fill events    │
│   Queue-position bars and lifecycle colors                   │
│   Hover → tooltip with order id + full lifecycle             │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ L2 depth heatmap (20% height) — NEW                          │
│   20-level heat, bid blue / ask red                          │
│   Template-match cosine similarity trace on top axis         │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ L1 footprint (20% height) — NEW                              │
│   BBO line + spread shading + BBO refresh markers            │
│   Tick-direction-streak + tick-acceleration subplot          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  shared scrubber ← existing replay_controls.js drives this
```

**Data source:** new WebSocket message type `triple_frame` streamed from
the server at replay time (§11.1). Payload schema matches
`TripleFrame` dataclass from §3.1 but in JSON form.

**Replay mode:** reads from `artifacts/p6lab/triple_view/{symbol}.parquet`
on disk via a new `/api/triple_view` endpoint (§11.1). Live mode: computed
on-the-fly by the engine runner as frames arrive.

**Synchronization:** clicking any panel at time t highlights
corresponding frames in the other two. Uses the existing replay
scrubber — no new time-axis code.

**Why this beats a notebook:** in a notebook, triple-view is a static
matplotlib render of a time window you pick by hand. In the UI it's a
live scrubbable replay, same one you already use for debugging the
pipeline. Zero new infrastructure cost, strictly more powerful.

### 10.2 Virtual Order Tool

**File:** `web/js/virtual_order_tool.js` (new)
**Activated by:** toolbar button "place virtual order"

**Interaction:**
1. User enables virtual-order mode with a toolbar toggle
2. Clicks any price level on the chart or DOM at any replay time
3. A modal asks: side (buy/sell), size (contracts), order type (limit /
   market / step-ahead), max horizon (seconds)
4. Frontend POSTs to `/api/fill_sim/interactive` (§11.5)
5. Server calls `p6lab.execution.fill_simulator.simulate_interactive`
   and returns the full trajectory
6. Frontend animates the order through time on the chart:
   - Queue-position bar shrinking as orders ahead get filled or cancelled
   - Green flash on fill, red flash on adverse exit, grey on timeout
   - Tooltip showing current P(fill), adverse ticks, realized PnL
7. After completion, a sidebar panel shows the `FillOutcome` summary

**Why this beats a notebook:** a notebook can show aggregate statistics
("25% of orders at quintile 3 fill within 2m") but it cannot show **this
specific order** at **this specific moment in this specific book state**.
That's the question a trader has at 10:31:04 when looking at a suspicious
spoof signal — and it's pure UI work.

The bulk-statistical version lives in notebook 05. **Both share
`p6lab.execution.fill_simulator` — one library, two entry points.**

### 10.3 Pattern Review Queue

**File:** `web/js/pattern_review_queue.js` (new)
**Route:** new page `/review` or modal overlay in the main app

**Workflow:**
1. After notebook 04 runs, it writes
   `artifacts/p6lab/pattern_library/mined_candidates/*.parquet` — one row
   per candidate cluster with its exemplar window timestamps
2. User opens the review queue page
3. Server reads `mined_candidates/` via new `/api/patterns/candidates`
   (§11.3)
4. Frontend loads one candidate at a time, auto-scrolls the replay to
   the first exemplar, and renders the Triple View Panel (§10.1)
5. Three buttons: **Accept** (promotes to `library.yaml` with
   `status: mined_approved`), **Reject** (marks `rejected` in
   `mined_decisions.parquet` so notebook 04 can skip it next run),
   **Next exemplar** (scrolls to the next exemplar of the same candidate
   for a second look)
6. Progress bar: "reviewed 23 / 87 candidates"
7. After review session, server writes decisions and refreshes library

**Why this beats a notebook:** notebook 08 as originally spec'd would
have rendered matplotlib grids of candidates with ipywidget buttons.
That's strictly worse than a purpose-built page: clickable triple view,
replay-synced context, and you can review ten candidates in the time
it takes a notebook to render one matplotlib figure.

This is the **human-in-the-loop gate** between unsupervised mining and
model training. Notebook 06 trains only on library entries with
`status ∈ {active, mined_approved}` — nothing unvetted reaches the
correlation engine.

### 10.4 Correlation Engine Feed

**File:** `web/js/correlation_feed.js` (new)
**Panel:** new sidebar panel beside the existing signal_bar

**What it shows:**
- Live stream of pattern matches from the running `CorrelationEngine`
- Each match is a row: timestamp, pattern_id, ensemble_score, tier
  (A/B/C), expected direction, expected move (ATR-normalized)
- Color by tier: green A, yellow B, grey C
- Click a row → replay jumps to that timestamp, triple view pops open
  at the match window
- Running histogram: match rate per minute, by tier

**Data source:** new WebSocket message type `correlation_match` pushed
by `correlation_api.py` (§11.4) whenever the engine emits a match above
the C tier threshold (0.60).

**Latency:** engine runs in the server's engine_runner loop alongside
the existing p6-v2 pipeline. Target <50ms per frame added to the
existing loop budget. Benchmarked in notebook 06 §10.

**Model loading:** server loads the latest approved model file from
`correlation_runs/models/` on startup. Reload endpoint
`POST /api/correlation/reload` swaps models without restarting the
server (§11.4).

**Why this beats a notebook:** the correlation engine's real job is
real-time inference on live / replayed L2. A notebook could dry-run it
on canned data but couldn't test the full live loop — that's exactly
what the UI + server integration tests.

### 10.5 Fragility Gauge Panel

**File:** `web/js/fragility_gauge.js` (new)
**Panel:** compact gauge in the existing stats header strip

**What it shows:**
- Live `FI_fast` (large gauge, <5ms update, red-yellow-green arc)
- Live `FI_full` (smaller gauge, <50ms update)
- Six sub-index bars below: DF / CF / RF / SF / FT / CIS
- Color flip on threshold crossings: 0.5 → yellow, 0.7 → red
- On FI_fast > 0.6, the `signal_bar.js` pattern detection threshold
  automatically lowers from 0.55 to 0.40 per
  [OB-reference.md:1701](./OB-reference.md#L1701)
- On FI_full > 0.7, the `backtest_controls.js` max size multiplier drops
  to 0.5 per [OB-reference.md:1721-1729](./OB-reference.md#L1721-L1729)

**Data source:** new WebSocket message type `fragility_update` pushed
on every snapshot from the engine runner.

**Why this beats a notebook:** FI is fundamentally a real-time signal.
Notebook 07 validates its historical predictive power; the UI is where
it actually warns you about impending cascades. Two separate jobs for
the same library.

---

## 11. Server Integration (`projects/p6-v2/server/`)

### 11.1 `replay_api.py` extensions

New endpoints:

| Method | Path | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/triple_view` | Query param `symbol`, `start_ms`, `end_ms`, `granularity`. Reads `artifacts/p6lab/triple_view/{symbol}.parquet`, returns JSON window. |
| WebSocket msg | `triple_frame` | Live-mode emission from engine_runner at each snapshot, schema mirrors `TripleFrame` |

The existing replay pipeline already streams per-frame data; this just
adds one more message type.

### 11.2 `backtest_api.py` extensions

Wires `p6lab.execution.cost_model` into the existing
`BacktestRunner.score()` path so that existing backtest runs get
realistic costs alongside the naive model. Toggle via query param
`cost_model=naive|realistic`.

### 11.3 `pattern_api.py` (new)

| Method | Path | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/patterns/library` | Current `library.yaml` as JSON |
| GET | `/api/patterns/candidates` | Lists mined candidates from notebook 04 |
| GET | `/api/patterns/candidate/{id}` | Single candidate with exemplar window timestamps |
| POST | `/api/patterns/candidate/{id}/accept` | Promotes to `library.yaml` |
| POST | `/api/patterns/candidate/{id}/reject` | Marks rejected in `mined_decisions.parquet` |

### 11.4 `correlation_api.py` (new)

| Method | Path | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/correlation/status` | Current engine state + loaded model version |
| POST | `/api/correlation/reload` | Reload latest `correlation_runs/models/*.pkl` |
| WebSocket msg | `correlation_match` | Server pushes engine output on each match |
| WebSocket msg | `fragility_update` | Server pushes FI values on each snapshot |

Runtime wiring: `engine_runner.py` instantiates `CorrelationEngine` on
startup (loading the latest approved model), runs it in the main loop
after each `OrderBookMetaPipeline.run()` call, publishes matches to the
WebSocket.

### 11.5 `fill_sim_api.py` (new)

| Method | Path | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| POST | `/api/fill_sim/interactive` | Body: order spec + timestamp. Calls `fill_simulator.simulate_interactive`, returns full `FillOutcome` with trajectory. |

Used exclusively by the virtual-order tool (§10.2). Batch notebook 05
imports `fill_simulator.simulate_bulk` directly; it does not go
through this API.

